<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="Chapter_07" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Mathematical Models</title>

  <introduction>
    <figure xml:id="fig_7_1">
      <caption>Mathematical models are just math ways of talking about natural phenomena.</caption>
      <image source="assets/chapter_07/fig_1.jpeg" width="70%"> </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The last thing we will cover about Excel is how to select a trendline type and what that actually means. It would be better to phrase that as “how to select the correct mathematical model”. <term>Mathematical modeling</term> is the process of using math to represent real-world phenomena. The reason the second terminology is better is because it correctly expresses the <term>thinking</term> that you must do to select a correct model. Before we jump into the different types of mathematical models (and associated trendlines) that you are expected to learn, we need to have a quick word on <term>thinking</term>.
    </p>
  </introduction>

</chapter>